Each problem has a 50/50 split between a positive and negative image, with 10 positive and 10 negative images per class. The goal is to predict the class of the positive image given the class of the negative image, using a model trained on ImageNet. 
 Natural Questions (short) was created in 2017 by Radford Neal and Hendriklimited. It has a natural 2-level ranking: First, you can pick any 5 images that you like the most, and then you can pick the 5 images in the worst possible way. The best results on this benchmark are 36.5%, so the best approach does not perform any bad image selection at all.

input (English text): TSE-NER stands for Turk Sentiment-Japanese Adversary Named-Query Language.  It is a small datasets which contain sentiment and translation annotations for both the Turkic and Japanese languages.  The TSE-NER dataset contains ten documents for training and one for test.  In order to evaluate models using the TSE-NER dataset,  the metric used depends on what type of analysis you want to perform.  If you want to find the accuracy of a model on a binary label classification problem, you can use the labels provided in the dataset for that purpose.  If you want to evaluate on the model's ability to identify sentiments, you can use the ROUGE metric [9] which computes the Recall on the UTUI Sentiment and JPN English language model.  There are also applications that allow for multi-label classification, such as identifying both sentiment and translation in the same model which can be done with a higher level of granularity by using the SentiWordNet label set [10].

Background
There is no shortage of datasets for image classification and object detection, so the challenge lies in choosing the right dataset for the right use case. For computer vision tasks, datasets consist of images annotated with categories and associated loss function. However, the purpose of a dataset varies significantly across research areas and the semantics of datasets vary significantly across them as well. Therefore, choosing the most suitable dataset for your application is key to achieve the best performance and build the most robust model.

A few factors are often considered when choosing the dataset:
1. It is commonly used in the state of the art
2. It is relatively small
3. It covers the category of interest
4. It contains a proper benchmark for model selection.

Note that the use of "benchmark" in the context of datasets is somewhat confusing. Benchmark in this case refers to an evaluation function that assesses model performance, rather than the model itself.
